Found in chirimoya-like Annonaceae by Guacamayo 250-300. After they feed there, we follow a consortship of Olio and Fiona. They take us running over to close to the east side of Chorongo (roughly CH 250) where they pause and go quiet and we lost sight of them. Then, at around 15:47 we see them copulating (we missed the start). They are about 30 m up, and Olio has his legs locked over Fionas. At 15:52, the copulation is over. We follow them as they move N and W across Q, Chorongo, and Matamata and wind up around 100 m NW of the Harpia/Matamata cross. We stick with them till around 17:15, then head back to the station. At one point around 17:00, one of them (Andres thinks Fiona) begins repeat barking, we think in response to hearing the terrestrial alarms of ant birds. Its also the case that Fiona and Olio are a bit separated at that point, so maybe that has something to do with the repeat barking.

After lunch, Ale and I go to find Chandler who has been tracking Lago G. We reach him at ~ Harpia 50 and begin following the signal of the female we darted 2 days ago. We follow it E (there are other monkeys around us) and we get to her around, I will guess, 14:00. We get a pretty good look at her feeding -- see the antenna sticking out nicely BEHIND her head and a round gold tag on the collar but not the pink nylon collar we'd given her. Then, we get confused because we see an adult male with a diamond shaped gold tag on his collar... this is Cuzco... and we hear his signal. So, it seems G and C (or parts thereof) are together. We again track the female and then see her once more, this time seeing very clearly her ROUND tag AND the pink collar. Ale and I leave to head back to camp when it starts to rain.
